1 Introduction

The objective of this work is to build several models and select the one that best fits the data. Based on the selected model, forecasts will be made using various strategies. The dataset used for this analysis is Wind Power Production in the US (2001-2022).

library(astsa)
library(xts)
library(forecast)
library(fpp)
library(ggplot2)
library(lubridate)
library(urca)
library(tseries)

library(scales)
library(zoo)
library(tsbox)

ts <- read.csv(file.choose())
ts_clean <- ts[c('date','wind_united_states')]

ts_clean$date <- as.character(ts_clean$date)
ts_clean$date <- mdy(paste(ts_clean$date))
ts_clean$date <- as.Date(paste(ts_clean$date, "01", sep = "-"), format = "%Y-%m-%d")


ts_clean1 <- ts(ts_clean$wind_united_states, start = c(year(min(ts_clean$date)), month(min(ts_clean$date))), frequency = 12)


ts_clean1 <- window(ts_clean1, start = c(2001, 1), end = c(2022, 12))



ggtsdisplay(ts_clean1, lag.max = 48, theme = theme_light(), main = "Wind United States")

2 EDA

First, we will split our dataset into a training set and a test set.

train_set <- window(ts_clean1, start = c(2001, 1), end = c(2020, 12))


test_set <- window(ts_clean1, start = c(2021, 1), end = c(2022, 12))


ggtsdisplay(train_set, lag.max = 48, theme = theme_light(), main= "Training Set (2001-2020)")

The time series plot indicates the presence of non-stationarity and heteroscedasticity.

The series shows a clear upward trend over the period from 2001 to 2020, as well as seasonality patterns with regular intervals.

The ACF plot suggests that the autocorrelations decrease slowly as the lag increases, which reinforces the existence of both trend and seasonality in the data. The cyclical pattern in the ACF points to a seasonal component with a defined periodicity.

The PACF plot displays significant spikes at a few initial lags, suggesting the presence of short-term dependencies. This implies the need to consider AR (auto-regressive) terms in the model, while the gradual decline in the ACF also supports the inclusion of MA (moving average) terms.

Following the Box-Jenkins methodology, we should first address heteroscedasticity and perform necessary transformations (e.g., logarithms/BoxCox and differencing) to stabilize the variance and achieve stationarity. Then, we will analyze the ACF and PACF of the transformed series to determine the appropriate SARIMA model.

lambda = BoxCox.lambda(train_set)

mts = ts_c(`Original training` = train_set, `Log training` = log(train_set), `BoxCox training` = BoxCox(train_set,
    lambda))

autoplot(mts, facet = T, ylab = NULL) + theme_light()

As the variance appears to change over time, indicating heteroscedasticity, the figure compares the plots of the original data, log-transformed, and Box-Cox transformed series.

To address this issue, the Box-Cox transformed version of the data will be used in subsequent analyses to stabilize the variance and ensure more reliable modeling.

3 Modelling strategy

We need to determine the number of differences required to make the series stationary.

This involves identifying the number of non-seasonal and seasonal unit roots to account for in the modeling process.

Using the nsdiffs function, we can calculate the necessary seasonal differences.

The analysis shows that the number of seasonal differences required is one (D=1), which corresponds to a 12-month period; therefore, the series will be differenced seasonally once.

train_set_boxcox <- BoxCox(train_set, lambda)

# Definir o objeto 'wind' como uma transformação de 'train_set'
wind <- ts(train_set_boxcox, start = start(train_set), frequency = frequency(train_set))

# Ajustar o ano inicial dinamicamente, com base no comprimento do conjunto
start_year <- start(train_set)[1] + (length(train_set) - length(wind)) / 12

# Atualizar o 'wind' caso seja necessário ajustar o início
wind <- ts(wind, start = c(start_year, 1), frequency = 12)

nsdiffs(wind) #deu 1 entao D=1 no modelo multiplicativo
[1] 1
ggtsdisplay(diff(wind, 12), lag.max = 48, theme = theme_light(), main = "Seasonally adjusted training data")

The series no longer exhibits seasonality but still appears non-stationary.

Using the ndiffs function, the result indicates that one non-seasonal difference (d=1) is sufficient to achieve stationarity in the series.

ndiffs(diff(wind,12)) #deu 1 entao d=1 no modelo multiplicativo
[1] 1

To verify, we will use the ndiffs function again after applying the differences. It should confirm stationarity by returning a value of 0.

ndiffs(diff(diff(wind,12),1), alpha=0.1)
[1] 0
wind_diff <- diff(diff(wind,12), 1)

3.1 Identifying the SARIMA model

ggtsdisplay(wind_diff, lag.max = 48, theme = theme_light(), main = "Stationary training data")

Based on the sample ACF and PACF analysis, we can determine the potential non-seasonal and seasonal AR and MA components for the models.

The ACF indicates the presence of a non-seasonal \(\text{MA}(1)\) and a seasonal \(\text{MA}(1)\), as significant correlations are observed at lags 1 and 12. This corresponds to \(q = 1\) and \(Q = 1\). Accordingly, one proposed model is:

  • \(M_1 = \text{SARIMA}(0, 1, 1) \times (0, 1, 1)_{12}\)

The PACF highlights a non-seasonal \(\text{AR}(2)\) and a seasonal \(\text{AR}(2)\), with notable correlations at lags 1, 12, and 24. This suggests \(p = 2\) and \(P = 2\). A corresponding model is:

  • \(M_2 = \text{SARIMA}(2, 1, 0) \times (2, 1, 0)_{12}\)

To explore other possibilities, we propose testing mixed configurations that combine the findings from the ACF and PACF analyses. The following models are considered for further evaluation:

  • \(M_3 = \text{SARIMA}(2, 1, 1) \times (2, 1, 1)_{12}\)

  • \(M_4 = \text{SARIMA}(0, 1, 1) \times (2, 1, 0)_{12}\)

  • \(M_5 = \text{SARIMA}(2, 1, 0) \times (0, 1, 1)_{12}\)

  • \(M_6 = \text{SARIMA}(2, 1, 1) \times (0, 1, 1)_{12}\)

  • \(M_7 = \text{SARIMA}(2, 1, 1) \times (2, 1, 0)_{12}\)

Each of these models should be carefully assessed by analyzing the diagnostic plots of residuals and verifying the significance of the estimated parameters to ensure proper fitting.

4 Forecasting strategies

The forecasting strategies relies on M4, M6 and M9 specifications, i.e. \(SARIMA(0,1,1)(2,1,0)_{12}\), \(SARIMA(2,1,1)(0,1,1)_{12}\) and \(SARIMA(9,1,0)(0,1,1)_{12}\), respectively.

4.1 Forecasting 24-months ahead

  • To forecast 24 steps ahead, we will use unique training data, which implies the use of a unique model fit.
# Subset the time series (exclude the last observation)
wind_train <- window(wind)

train_set_boxcox <- BoxCox(train_set, lambda)
test_set <- window(ts_clean1, start = c(2021, 1), end = c(2022, 12))



print(test_set)

First, we’ll do the forecasts for M4.

#Forecast 24 meses para M4
M4.fit_plots = Arima(train_set_boxcox, order = c(0, 1, 1), seasonal = c(2, 1, 0))
all.equal(M4$fit$coef, M4.fit_plots$coef)
[1] TRUE
#dá true
M4.fct.v1 = forecast(M4.fit_plots, h = 24, level = 95)

Plotting the forecasts

# Reverter a transformação Box-Cox no forecast
M4.fct.v1_original_scale <- M4.fct.v1
M4.fct.v1_original_scale$mean <- InvBoxCox(M4.fct.v1$mean, lambda)

# Reverter a transformação nos limites inferior e superior (linha por linha/coluna)
M4.fct.v1_original_scale$lower <- apply(M4.fct.v1$lower, 2, InvBoxCox, lambda)
M4.fct.v1_original_scale$upper <- apply(M4.fct.v1$upper, 2, InvBoxCox, lambda)


# Criar o gráfico com a série observada e a previsão em escala original
autoplot(ts_c(Observed = ts_clean1,

Organising the forecasts and checking the model accuracy.

# Criando a tabela de previsões para M4 na escala original
fct.tab_M4 <- data.frame(
  Month = as.yearmon(time(test_set)), 
  Observed = as.numeric(test_set),  # Converter test_set para numérico
  Forecast = round(M4.fct.v1_original_scale$mean, 2), 
  Error = round((as.numeric(test_set) - M4.fct.v1_original_scale$mean), 2), 
  Error_PCT = percent(
    (as.vector((as.numeric(test_set) - M4.fct.v1_original_scale$mean) / as.numeric(test_set))), 
    accuracy = 0.01
  ),

4.2 Forecasting 24 months with 1-step ahead - Interaction

  • This forecasting strategy assumes that we know the new data at the time of forecasting, rather than fitting a new model based on new data.

  • Forecasting uses the fitted model to predict the new data.

Plotting the forecasts for M4

# converting the ts object into a DF
ts_clean1_boxcox <- BoxCox(ts_clean1, lambda)
ts_df = ts_df(ts_clean1_boxcox)

# forecasting 24 times 1-step ahead for M4
output = data.frame()
for (i in 1:24) {
  df_select = ts_df %>%
    filter(time <= as.Date("2020-12-01") %m+% months(i))
  
  ts_select = ts(df_select$value, freq = 12, end = c(year(tail(df_select$time,
                                                               1)), month(tail(df_select$time, 1))))
  
  fit = Arima(ts_select, model = M4.fit_plots)
  
  aux = bind_cols(time = as.Date("2021-01-01") %m+% months(i), value = tail(fitted(fit),
                                                                            1))
  
  output = bind_rows(output, aux)
}

# converting output to TS
M4.fct.v2 = ts_ts(output)
M4.fct.v2_original_scale <- M4.fct.v2
M4.fct.v2_original_scale <- InvBoxCox(M4.fct.v2_original_scale, lambda)

# forecasts plot
autoplot(ts_c(Observed = ts_clean1, `Fixed training (1-step ahead forecast)` = M4.fct.v2_original_scale),

4.3 Forecasting 24 months with 1-step ahead - Expanding windows

  • In the expanding window strategy, the training sample size is sequentially increased by one time unit.

  • The forecasts generated are based on multiple fitting models.

Plotting the forecasts for M4

# converting the ts object into a DF
ts_df = ts_df(ts_clean1_boxcox)

# forecasting M1 specification with expanding windows
output = data.frame()
for (i in 0:23) {
  df_select = ts_df %>%
    filter(time <= as.Date("2020-12-01") %m+% months(i))
  
  ts_select = ts(df_select$value, freq = 12, end = c(year(tail(df_select$time,
                                                               1)), month(tail(df_select$time, 1))))
  
  fit = Arima(ts_select, order = c(0, 1, 1), seasonal = c(2, 1, 0))
  
  M4.fct.expw = forecast(fit, h = 1, level = 95)
  
  aux = bind_cols(time = as.Date("2021-01-01") %m+% months(i), model_specification = as.character(fit),
                  value = M4.fct.expw$mean)
  
  output = bind_rows(output, aux)
}

4.4 Forecasting 24 Months with 1-Step Ahead - Recursive Windows

  • In the recursive window strategy, the training sample size remains fixed during the forecast generation.

  • However, at each step, the set of observations in the training sample is updated.

  • The training window shifts by one time unit to produce a new forecast.

  • Forecasts are generated based on multiple models fitted throughout the process.

M4

ts_df = ts_df(ts_clean1_boxcox)

output = data.frame()
for (i in 0:23) {
  df_select = ts_df %>%
    filter(time >= as.Date("2000-01-01") %m+% months(i) & time <= as.Date("2020-12-01") %m+% months(i))
  
  ts_select = ts(df_select$value, freq = 12, end = c(year(tail(df_select$time, 1)), month(tail(df_select$time, 1))))
  
  fit = Arima(ts_select, order = c(0, 1, 1), seasonal = c(2, 1, 0))
  
  M4.fct.recw = forecast(fit, h = 1, level = 95)
  
  aux = bind_cols(time = as.Date("2021-01-01") %m+% months(i), model_specification = as.character(fit), value = M4.fct.recw$mean)
  
  output = bind_rows(output, aux)
}

# Converting output to TS
M4.fct.v4 = ts_ts(output)
M4.fct.v4_original_scale <- M4.fct.v4
M4.fct.v4_original_scale <- InvBoxCox(M4.fct.v4_original_scale, lambda)

# Forecasts plot

M9

output = data.frame()
for (i in 0:23) {
  df_select = ts_df %>%
    filter(time >= as.Date("2000-01-01") %m+% months(i) & time <= as.Date("2020-12-01") %m+% months(i))
  
  ts_select = ts(df_select$value, freq = 12, end = c(year(tail(df_select$time, 1)), month(tail(df_select$time, 1))))
  
  fit = Arima(ts_select, order = c(9, 1, 0), seasonal = c(0, 1, 1))
  
  M9.fct.recw = forecast(fit, h = 1, level = 95)
  
  aux = bind_cols(time = as.Date("2021-01-01") %m+% months(i), model_specification = as.character(fit), value = M9.fct.recw$mean)
  
  output = bind_rows(output, aux)
}

# Converting output to TS
M9.fct.v4 = ts_ts(output)
M9.fct.v4_original_scale <- M9.fct.v4
M9.fct.v4_original_scale <- InvBoxCox(M9.fct.v4_original_scale, lambda)

Best Forecasting Strategy for All Models:

Expanding training (1-step ahead forecast) is the best strategy for all models (M4, M6, M9), as it consistently shows:

  • Lower ACF1, indicating that the errors are not autocorrelated,

  • Lower Theil’s U, which means the model performs better than a simple average or constant value.

Best Model:

M6 appears to be the best model, as it shows good results in terms of RMSE, MAE, MAPE, ACF1, and Theil’s U, when using the Expanding training (1-step ahead forecast) strategy.

  • RMSE and MAE are relatively low compared to the other models, with the best ACF1 among the three.

  • Theil’s U is the lowest among the three, indicating that M6 provides better forecasts compared to the reference model.

Conclusion:

  • Best Strategy: Expanding training (1-step ahead forecast)

  • Best Model: M6 (with the Expanding training strategy).
